{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893774/1930102701/0471.xml":{"full_text":"MORROW RACE\nSTIRS JERSEY\nTwo Candidates Renounce\nProhibition As Third\nUpholds Measure\nNEWARK. N. J., Oct. 27\u2014(JPh\nThe contest for United States sena\ntor In New Jersey has robbed this\nyear\u2019s campaign of the usual apathj\nof an off-year.\nDwight W. Morrow became a can\ndidate just a few months ago and\nthe nation took notice. He was a\nfresh figure In the game of politics\nwhich now has him pitted against\nAlexander Simpson and Miss Thel\nma Parkinson, Democrats and\nagainst the nominees of the prohi\nbition, communist and socialist par\nties.\nSimpson Is a candidate for the\nfull senatorial term of six years\nMiss Parkinson for the unexpirec\nterm of Walter E. Edge, and Morrow\nfor both. Miss Parkinson went froir\nSmith college into politics.\nFor the most part, New Jersey hat\nturned its eyes and ears towarc\ntwo men. heard both of them re\nnounce prohibition, one of their\nli-.ud President Hoover, the othei\nbitterly assail him.\nMorrow answers no charges. Hi\ndoes not mention his adversaries\nNeither does he criticize the Issue!\nthey raise. He makes no specific\nrequests for votes for himself; hi\nasks only that the people exerclsi\ntheir franchise.\nSimpson, spectacular of speech\nhas raised a warning against sup\nport of endorsers of President Hoov\ner and the national administration\nlest business depression continue.\nSimpson Is a man of slogans anc\nalliterations. Morrow is \"Dwight\nWorship Morrow\" to Simpson. A\nvote for the republican, he warns\nis signification of approval of \"Mor\nrow, Morgan and misery\nMorrow was formerly partner ol\nJ. P. Morgan and Co.\nMorrow, warmly commending th<\npresident, holds that the courage ol\nthe people will constitute the majoi\ncontribution to the return of pros\nperity. He pleads against exag\ngeration of business depression and\nunemployment.\nSince his declaration for repeal ol\nthe eighteenth amendment. Mor\nrow has been advanced as a poten\ntial candidate for the presidency\nHe refuses to take such talk serious\nly. He has said he looks forward\nwith \"confidence and with pleasure'\nto voting for the renomination and\nre-election of President Hoover ir\n1932\nA full delegation of twelve will bi\nelected to the house of representa\ntives. a complement of sixty sent t<\nthe state assembly and eight state\nsenators chosen.\nFISHER\n(Continued from page 1)\nIL_\nMmter; Chapman Ranch. A R\nVetter; Falfurrias, J. A. Ruffner;\nGeorge West. P. S. Connell; Goliad\nFannin, S. R. Honvood; Gregory\nIngleside. A. T. White; Hebbron\nville-Mirando. W. 8. Highsmith, Jr.;\nKarnes City. O. O. Moore; Kenedy\nR. E. Duke; Kingsville, M. D. Coun\ncil; Kingsville Ct., D. G. Hardt;\nMathis, W. D. Williamson; Odem\nM. L. Darby: Robstown, Stanlej\nHaver: Rockport. J Troy Hickman\nRunge, Fred A Banks; Sinton. F\nM. Jackson; Taft, Fred J. Brucks,\nSkidmore. W. L Jenkins; Three\nRivers, Robert Paine.\nLlano District\nPresiding elder, W. M. Rader\nArt. R. W. Radftzky; Bandera-Me\ndina, G. T. Hester; Bertram, S M\nBailey; Blanco and Johnson City\nJ. H Thompson; Briggs Ct., V. L\nWunneburger; Burnet, A. G. Cole\nman; Caste 11, J. H. E. William;\nCenter Point and Boeme, O. C. Ha\nley; Richland Springs and Chero\nkee. J. M. Lewis; Comfort, V. L\nSherman; Ftedonta, T. K Ander\nson; Fredericksburg. R Gammen\nthaler; Goldthwaite. H H. Dare;\nGold watte Ct.. W. J. Benningfield\nsupplv; Harpers Ct.. F. G. Clark;\nKerrville. Shan M. Hull; Lampasas\nW M. Lane; Llanb, J W. Black;\nLometa. L. C. Mathis; Liberty Hill\nE. J. Sloan; Leander. Leslie Mc\nDaniel, supply; Marble Falls, S. J\nMcLean; Mason. J V. Davis; Mul\nlin Ct., T. M. Mitchell; San Sab?\nF. H. Hamner; Starr Ct, H. F\nMoreland, supply; Student, 8. M\nU.. E. H. Miller.\nSan Angelo District\nPresiding elder. S. L. Batchelor\nBrady. W. N. Carl; Christoval Ct\nW. B. Woodruff, supply; Eden*\nMillersview. J. L. Bryant; Eldo\nrado. J. D.